Here's a complete example of a C# MCP server wrapping a REST API via stdio transport.

---

### **Program.cs** — stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: route all logging to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient for DI — tools receive it via constructor injection
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("api", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();  // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

### **ApiTools.cs** — tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a post by its numeric ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPost(
        [Description("The post ID (1-100)")] int id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching post {Id}", id);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var post = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>(
            $"/posts/{id}", cancellationToken);
        return post.ToString();
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts by a specific user.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPostsByUser(
        [Description("The user ID to filter by")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var posts = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>(
            $"/posts?userId={userId}", cancellationToken);
        return posts.ToString();
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false), Description("Create a new post.")]
    public async Task<string> CreatePost(
        [Description("Title of the post")] string title,
        [Description("Body content of the post")] string body,
        [Description("Author's user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var response = await client.PostAsJsonAsync("/posts",
            new { title, body, userId }, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var result = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
        return result;
    }
}
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in constructor (like `ApiTools` above) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | Services as method params alongside tool params |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, etc.) are resolved at invocation time and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

Built-in injectable types (no registration needed):
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — report progress to client

To scaffold this project:
```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
# then replace the generated files with the code above
```
